For mooc demo

This file aims for you to understand how to read in textfile, do some basic cleaning and visualize the data with a word cloud and to build a corpus.

This by no means help you to finish the entire capstone.

loading the required libraries

library(plyr); library(ggplot2); library(reshape2); library(gridExtra)
library(tm); library(SnowballC); library(qdap); library(RWeka)
library(wordcloud); library(RColorBrewer)

reading in the dataset

blogs <- readRDS("blogs.RData")
news <- readRDS("news.RData")
twitter <- readRDS("twit.RData")

texts <- list(blogs=blogs,news=news,twitter=twitter)
set.seed(20)

preparing the data and cleaning the data

#line count in each of the dataset
lineCount <- llply(texts, length)
lineCount
## $blogs
## [1] 899288
## 
## $news
## [1] 1010242
## 
## $twitter
## [1] 2360148
#sampling a portion of it 
#in this case, we sample 0.1% from each of the dataset
sample_percent = 0.001
textsS <- llply(seq_along(texts), 
                function(i) sample(texts[[i]], ceiling(sample_percent * lineCount[[i]])))
#remove other stuff to make it more memory 
remove(blogs,news,twitter,texts)

class(textsS)
## [1] "list"
#convert to character 
textsS <- do.call(c, textsS)

class(textsS)
## [1] "character"
#sent_detect - detect sentences and split them accordingly 
#example
s <- "This is a sentence. This another---but with dash-like structures, and some commas.
Maybe another with question marks? Sure!"
sent_detect(s, language = "en")
## [1] "This is a sentence."                                           
## [2] "This another---but with dash-like structures, and some commas."
## [3] "Maybe another with question marks?"                            
## [4] "Sure!"
#add a "|" in each sentence incase you need to split it afterwards 
textsS <- sent_detect(paste0(textsS, "|"))

#remove punc
textsS <- removePunctuation(textsS, preserve_intra_word_dashes = T)

#remove white spaces
textsS <- stripWhitespace(textsS)

#convert to lower text
textsS <- tolower(textsS)
set.seed(1337)
wordCount <- sort(termFreq(PlainTextDocument(textsS)), decreasing = T)
wordcloud(names(wordCount), wordCount, scale = c(5,1), max.words = 200, 
          colors = brewer.pal(9, "Set1"))

set.seed(1337)
BigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 2))
bigramCount <- sort(termFreq(PlainTextDocument(textsS), control = list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer)),
                    decreasing = T)
wordcloud(names(bigramCount), bigramCount, max.words = 200, 
          colors = brewer.pal(9, "Set1"))

set.seed(1337)
TrigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 3, max = 3))
trigramCount <- sort(termFreq(PlainTextDocument(textsS), control = list(tokenize = TrigramTokenizer)),
                     decreasing = T)
wordcloud(names(trigramCount), trigramCount, scale = c(3, 0.5), min.freq = 1,max.words = 100, 
          colors = brewer.pal(9, "Set1"))

set.seed(1337)
quadgramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 4, max = 4))
quadgramCount <- sort(termFreq(PlainTextDocument(textsS), control = list(tokenize = quadgramTokenizer)),
                     decreasing = T)
wordcloud(names(quadgramCount), quadgramCount, scale = c(3, 0.5), min.freq = 1,max.words = 100, 
          colors = brewer.pal(9, "Set1"))

ggplot function

hist_ngram <- function(data,first_n=15,label = 'bigram'){
  data = as.data.frame(data)
  data$word <- row.names(data)
  names(data) <- c("freq","word")
  y_label = paste("Most common",label,'in text sample')
  plot <- ggplot(data[1:first_n,], aes(x=reorder(word,freq), y=freq, fill=freq)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    theme_bw() +
    coord_flip() +
    theme(axis.title.y = element_blank()) +
    labs(y="Frequency", title=y_label)
  return(plot)
}

hist_ngram(wordCount,label='alone-gram')

hist_ngram(bigramCount,label='bi-gram')

hist_ngram(trigramCount,label='tri-gram')

hist_ngram(quadgramCount,label='quad-gram')
